1. Residual Analysis


After time series model is fit, we want to check the residual for

  • Randomness (no autocorrelation)

  • Heteroscedasticity (constatnt conditional variance)

  • Normality (not important in ARMA)



Given residuals, \(\hat e_t\), we want to see if it is an uncorrelated sequence or not.

  • Plot ACF/PACF
  • Ljung-Box test for randomness
  • McLeod-Li test



2. Test for Randomness



Ljung-Box test


  • With sample ACF \(\hat \rho(h)\), \[ Q = n(n+2) \sum_{h=1}^H \frac{ \hat \rho(h)^2}{n-h} \]

  • Under the null hypothesis of uncorrelation, \(Q \sim \chi^2(H)\).

  • Use as one-sided upper tailed test.

  • Parameter \(H\) must be chosen by hand. Use couple of different values.



Example: L-B test

  D  <- read.csv("https://nmimoto.github.io/datasets/gtemp.csv")
  D1 <- ts(D, start=c(1880), freq=1)
  D2 <- diff(D1)

  plot(D2)

  library(forecast)

  Fit1 <- Arima(D2, order=c(2,0,0), include.mean=FALSE)

  res <- Fit1$resid

  Box.test(res,   lag = 15, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  res
## X-squared = 30.756, df = 15, p-value = 0.00947
  Box.test(res,   lag = 20, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  res
## X-squared = 34.615, df = 20, p-value = 0.02225
  Box.test(res,   lag = 25, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  res
## X-squared = 38.631, df = 25, p-value = 0.04009



Example: Null Distribution of L-B test

  X <- rnorm(100, 2, 4)

  Box.test(res, lag=15, type="Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  res
## X-squared = 30.756, df = 15, p-value = 0.00947
  n=100
  sam.acf <- acf(X)$acf

  Q <- n*(n+2)*sum( sam.acf[2:16]^2/(n-(1:15)) )

  Q <- 0
  for (i in 1:1000) {
    X <- rnorm(100, 2, 4)
    sam.acf <- acf(X, plot=FALSE)$acf
    Q[i] <- n*(n+2)*sum( sam.acf[2:16]^2/(n-(1:15)) )
  }

  hist(Q, freq=FALSE)
  t <- seq(0, 50, .1)
  lines(t, dchisq(t, 15), col="red")




3. Test for Heteroscedasticity



McLeod-Li test

Instead of testing \(Y_t\), test \(Y_t^2\) for uncorrelation.

Use same test statistic as Ljung-Box, replace \(Y_t\) with \(Y_t^2\).



Example: McLeod-Li test

  A <- Fit1$resid

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1, 2))
  plot(A)
  plot(A^2)

  acf(A)
  acf(A^2)

  layout(1,1,1)

  Box.test(A^2, lag = 15, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  A^2
## X-squared = 24.777, df = 15, p-value = 0.05302
  Box.test(A^2, lag = 20, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  A^2
## X-squared = 30.416, df = 20, p-value = 0.06339



4. Test for Normality



Test for Normality

Given sequence \(Y_t\), we want to test if it came from Normal distribution. (\(\mu\) and \(\si\) unspecified).

  • q-q normal plot
  • Jarque-Bera test



qq-normal plot

  X <- rnorm(100, 2, 5)
  qqnorm(X)



Jarque-Bera Test for Normality

  • Normal distribution has skewness 0, and kurtosis of 3. for any \(\mu\) and \(\sigma^2\).

    \[ \mbox{Skewness} = \frac{E[(Y_t - \mu )^3]}{ \mbox{SD}(Y_t)^{3}} \hspace10mm \mbox{ Kurtosis } = \frac{E[(Y_t - \mu )^4]}{ \mbox{SD}(Y_t)^{4}} \] \[ JB = \frac{n}{6} \Big(S^2 + \frac{1}{4}(K-3)^2\Big) \] where \(S\) is sample skewness, and \(K\) is sample kurtosis.

  • Asymptotically \(JB\) has \(\chi^2(2)\) distribution under the normality.



Example: Testing Normality

  library(tseries)  # load tseries package   ( install.packge("tseries") if first time)

  # acf(res)
  # acf(res, na.action=na.pass)
  res <- Fit1$resid
  res <- res[ which(is.na(res)==0) ]    # remove NA from res

  jarque.bera.test(res)
## 
##  Jarque Bera Test
## 
## data:  res
## X-squared = 2.0672, df = 2, p-value = 0.3557



5. Custom Functions



Making Your Own Function in R


  x <- 5
  f <- exp(5+4)
  f

  f <- function(x){
    exp(x+4)
  }
  f(5)

All of above function is put into my function called Randomness.tests(). You can load that into R by copy and pasting the following line.

  #--- This line copy and paste Basic Functions on class web page
  source("https://nmimoto.github.io/R/TS-00.txt")

  #- Use the function as below
  res <- Fit1$resid
  
  Randomness.tests(res)


Summary

Residuals from any time-sereis analysis must be checked for:

  • Randomness (for uncorrelation) - (e.g. Ljung-Box test)

  • Heteroscedasticity (Randomness of squared series) - (e.g. McLeod-Li test)

  • Normality - (e.g. qqplot and Jarque-Bera test)

  • Below R code will load the all-in-one function (you need package installed already)

  res <- Fit1$resid
  source("https://nmimoto.github.io/R/TS-00.txt")

  Randomness.tests(res)
  
  Stationarity.tests(res)

  • To test if the true mean is \(0\) or not, we must construct CI for \(\mu\), and see if \(0\) is inside the CI or not.

  • For autocorrelated data, variance of the sample mean is bigger than the random sample case. We must estimate the sample mean variance by summing up sample ACVF.
